{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[2]", "headings": "['Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample']"}, "page_content": "Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample\nAs highlighted in the research by Rich (2018) and Borysov et al. (2019), population synthesis methods typically consist of three steps: 1). Creating a starting solution that generates a synthetic pool of individuals to represent various attribute combinations. This is usually done based on the available microsamples. 2). The fitting stage involves estimating the weighting factors for the synthetic pools to create a representative synthetic population for future targets. 3). The allocation stage involves the generation and assignment of synthetic agents to ABM transport models. This paper exclusively concentrates on the initial stage, which involves creating suitable representative samples for a specific population, without taking into account how these samples will align with future objectives. This step is critical because any underlying error in it will propagate into the ABM models, affecting the forecast results.", "type": "Document"}}